WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.360 --> 00:00:07.935
Prof: As you may have
noticed, the course has been

00:00:07.935 --> 00:00:10.170
proceeding somewhat
historically.

00:00:10.170 --> 00:00:14.712
First with pre-primate animals,
the whole evolution of sex from

00:00:14.712 --> 00:00:19.700
things that swam in the ocean,
and then we discussed the

00:00:19.700 --> 00:00:23.710
primate mating system as you've
seen--

00:00:23.710 --> 00:00:28.370
in the same sense as on the
board.

00:00:28.370 --> 00:00:32.607
The first--the pre-primate is a
few millions of years--I'm

00:00:32.607 --> 00:00:35.210
sorry, tens of millions of
years;

00:00:35.210 --> 00:00:40.760
primates maybe ten million
years or so.

00:00:40.760 --> 00:00:44.459
Then last time we started
discussing the transition from

00:00:44.459 --> 00:00:47.015
ape to human,
and evolutionarily modern

00:00:47.015 --> 00:00:50.850
humans date to something like
150 thousand years ago.

00:00:50.850 --> 00:00:56.227
We're coming up to time and
today we're going to discuss

00:00:56.227 --> 00:00:59.650
fully anatomically modern
humans.

00:00:59.650 --> 00:01:03.197
They have the same brain
capacity that we do,

00:01:03.197 --> 00:01:04.890
etcetera, etcetera.
 

00:01:04.890 --> 00:01:08.706
The earliest groups that we
have any kind of decent

00:01:08.706 --> 00:01:13.209
demographic data on are hunter
gatherers which would include

00:01:13.209 --> 00:01:17.714
cavemen and people that are
hunter gatherers but do not live

00:01:17.714 --> 00:01:18.860
in caves.
 

00:01:18.860 --> 00:01:24.322
Last time we asked why there
were so few chimps and so many

00:01:24.322 --> 00:01:29.692
humans and today we're going to
ask very similar questions

00:01:29.692 --> 00:01:31.602
about--
we're going to start with,

00:01:31.602 --> 00:01:32.709
we're going to cover a lot
more;

00:01:32.709 --> 00:01:36.134
we're going to ask very similar
questions about hunter

00:01:36.134 --> 00:01:36.910
gatherers.
 

00:01:36.910 --> 00:01:40.170
There never was a great density
of hunter gatherers.

00:01:40.170 --> 00:01:46.910
There is certainly not now and
the question is,

00:01:46.910 --> 00:01:47.790
why?
 

00:01:47.790 --> 00:01:50.540
If you look where hunter
gatherers live now they--

00:01:50.540 --> 00:01:53.232
each small group,
and the again the small group

00:01:53.232 --> 00:01:56.920
is the same size we've been
talking about something like 40,

00:01:56.920 --> 00:02:00.284
are spread out over a very
large area and they use that

00:02:00.284 --> 00:02:03.400
area to hunt in and to collect
fruits and nuts,

00:02:03.400 --> 00:02:07.269
and whatever they can get from
the trees.

00:02:07.269 --> 00:02:11.972
It looks like a very simple
question, why is the density of

00:02:11.972 --> 00:02:14.080
hunter gatherers so low?
 

00:02:14.080 --> 00:02:16.658
Why are there so few of them?
 

00:02:16.658 --> 00:02:19.288
For a long time,
the answer was:

00:02:19.288 --> 00:02:21.750
they didn't have much food.
 

00:02:21.750 --> 00:02:28.008
That they needed all this space
to get enough food to survive,

00:02:28.008 --> 00:02:34.270
and if they overpopulated that
space they couldn't survive.

00:02:34.270 --> 00:02:38.026
In sort of modern hubris,
we looked back and thought

00:02:38.026 --> 00:02:41.634
hunter gatherer is a very
inefficient form of food

00:02:41.634 --> 00:02:45.389
gathering,
not modern, and we're so much

00:02:45.389 --> 00:02:47.400
better than them now.
 

00:02:47.400 --> 00:02:58.848
The data is quite clear on some
part of those assumptions;

00:02:58.848 --> 00:03:02.060
hunter gatherers,
at the time when all human

00:03:02.060 --> 00:03:05.346
beings were in the stage of
hunter gatherers,

00:03:05.346 --> 00:03:09.080
before--farming starts about
10,000 years ago.

00:03:09.080 --> 00:03:16.479
There's--what is the number
here?

00:03:16.479 --> 00:03:19.455
There may have been like two
million people on the whole

00:03:19.455 --> 00:03:19.889
earth.
 

00:03:19.889 --> 00:03:23.060
Remember I said hunter
gatherers spread out of Africa,

00:03:23.060 --> 00:03:25.740
spread amazingly over the whole
earth,

00:03:25.740 --> 00:03:28.776
and maybe the total population
of humans at that time was

00:03:28.776 --> 00:03:30.729
something like two million
people.

00:03:30.729 --> 00:03:36.407
Now we have over six billion
people, that's an increase of

00:03:36.407 --> 00:03:41.586
3,000 times in the human
population, so clearly there

00:03:41.586 --> 00:03:45.669
were fewer hunter gatherers than
now.

00:03:45.669 --> 00:03:49.529
This is a very--you'll see this
in lots of discussions of this

00:03:49.529 --> 00:03:52.061
field, but it's a very
elementary kind of

00:03:52.061 --> 00:03:53.199
consideration.
 

00:03:53.199 --> 00:03:56.900
It talks about the long scale
of human demography,

00:03:56.900 --> 00:04:01.783
of human population growth,
and we came out of being other

00:04:01.783 --> 00:04:06.349
species of primate,
of hominids and we gradually

00:04:06.349 --> 00:04:09.508
grew up to some sort of a limit.
 

00:04:09.508 --> 00:04:14.185
There's the idea that the
various productive systems that

00:04:14.185 --> 00:04:17.641
we use,
like hunter gathering--limit is

00:04:17.641 --> 00:04:21.110
some sort of a carrying capacity
limit,

00:04:21.110 --> 00:04:24.867
and so the idea is that the
human population increased until

00:04:24.867 --> 00:04:28.690
it reached a limit and then for
a very long period of time it

00:04:28.690 --> 00:04:30.730
can't get beyond that limit.
 

00:04:30.730 --> 00:04:35.720
Then 10,000 years ago,
maybe it's 12,000,

00:04:35.720 --> 00:04:38.894
farming is invented and all of
a sudden the whole system

00:04:38.894 --> 00:04:41.579
changes,
there's many more people and we

00:04:41.579 --> 00:04:44.160
jump up and then again reach a
limit,

00:04:44.160 --> 00:04:48.084
and we'll talk about that as
some Malthusian limit in this

00:04:48.084 --> 00:04:51.569
particular period,
later we'll discuss that,

00:04:51.569 --> 00:04:55.894
and then around here the
industrial revolution happens

00:04:55.894 --> 00:05:00.300
and all of a sudden the
population increases again.

00:05:00.300 --> 00:05:03.480
This is a logarithmic scale so
it's not linear.

00:05:03.480 --> 00:05:06.500
Each of these jumps is by a
factor of several thousand.

00:05:06.500 --> 00:05:10.357
That's a very,
very schematized version of

00:05:10.357 --> 00:05:16.379
human demographic history and
we're talking about this period.

00:05:16.379 --> 00:05:20.406
What limited hunter gatherers
to this level whereas farmers

00:05:20.406 --> 00:05:22.350
could go up to this level.
 

00:05:22.350 --> 00:05:28.252
Again, the obvious answer and
looking at this kind of rough

00:05:28.252 --> 00:05:31.000
data is that it was food.
 

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:35.088
Whoever then--archeologists,
paleontologists go and actually

00:05:35.088 --> 00:05:39.105
try to examine this and there
turns out to be the data does

00:05:39.105 --> 00:05:41.740
not fit that theory terribly
well.

00:05:41.740 --> 00:05:44.310
What do archeologists do?
 

00:05:44.310 --> 00:05:50.136
They dig up skeletons and they
have a good representative set

00:05:50.136 --> 00:05:55.574
of skeletons from the last 7,000
years in North and South

00:05:55.574 --> 00:05:56.740
America.
 

00:05:56.740 --> 00:06:01.901
One study looked at more than
12,500 skeletons so we're

00:06:01.901 --> 00:06:05.819
talking about a good scientific
sample.

00:06:05.819 --> 00:06:06.980
What did they find out?
 

00:06:06.980 --> 00:06:10.836
These were set into
communities, and communities

00:06:10.836 --> 00:06:14.529
lasted so much time,
so you can date the whole

00:06:14.529 --> 00:06:18.060
archeological site to a certain
period.

00:06:18.060 --> 00:06:21.392
The medical anthropologists got
into it and started looking at

00:06:21.392 --> 00:06:23.579
the bones and dentition and all
this,

00:06:23.579 --> 00:06:25.947
and not only did they find the
violence we talked about last

00:06:25.947 --> 00:06:28.410
time,
but these people were also sick.

00:06:28.410 --> 00:06:31.069
They had diseases at different
times.

00:06:31.069 --> 00:06:33.874
You could see bone problems and
how well the bones grew and from

00:06:33.874 --> 00:06:36.190
the teeth how much calcium they
had, and all this.

00:06:36.190 --> 00:06:39.365
What does it turn out,
that contrary to the idea of

00:06:39.365 --> 00:06:43.430
progress that you'd think the
later people were more healthy,

00:06:43.430 --> 00:06:46.529
in fact, it was earlier people
in the--

00:06:46.529 --> 00:06:50.750
the earlier individuals that
were healthier.

00:06:50.750 --> 00:06:54.105
As time goes on,
the skeletons get less and less

00:06:54.105 --> 00:06:58.245
healthy, that they're getting
less food and less good food,

00:06:58.245 --> 00:07:00.959
and were more subject to
diseases.

00:07:00.959 --> 00:07:05.540
It was quite a shocker when
this status started coming out.

00:07:05.540 --> 00:07:10.846
The researchers attributed this
decline in health in large part

00:07:10.846 --> 00:07:13.329
to the rise in agriculture.
 

00:07:13.329 --> 00:07:16.973
Two main factors they say,
the rise of agriculture and the

00:07:16.973 --> 00:07:20.233
rise of urban living,
and we'll talk about the urban

00:07:20.233 --> 00:07:21.639
story in a moment.
 

00:07:21.639 --> 00:07:25.423
If you again go like we did
last time from the archeology to

00:07:25.423 --> 00:07:29.079
the anthropology and look at
current hunter gatherers,

00:07:29.079 --> 00:07:33.053
it's a little bit of a
distorted study because nowadays

00:07:33.053 --> 00:07:37.396
almost all hunter gatherers have
been pushed out of the good

00:07:37.396 --> 00:07:42.319
lands that they used to live in,
into very marginal lands.

00:07:42.319 --> 00:07:45.134
You know this from
U.S. History in high school,

00:07:45.134 --> 00:07:48.682
how the European farmers pushed
the very earlier farmers or

00:07:48.682 --> 00:07:51.620
hunter gatherers of the American
Indians,

00:07:51.620 --> 00:07:54.740
the Native Americans into
Arizona, into desert,

00:07:54.740 --> 00:07:58.218
into the Badlands in the West,
the dry Badlands and to the

00:07:58.218 --> 00:08:02.374
West of the U.S.,
farming peoples push hunter

00:08:02.374 --> 00:08:06.069
gatherers into inhospitable
land.

00:08:06.069 --> 00:08:11.898
There's a story in the
Smithsonian Magazine recently

00:08:11.898 --> 00:08:14.870
about Pygmies in Africa.
 

00:08:14.870 --> 00:08:16.947
I don't know if you know a
little bit about the history of

00:08:16.947 --> 00:08:19.540
African demography,
which we'll also cover,

00:08:19.540 --> 00:08:22.810
but the Bantus have expanded
from south--

00:08:22.810 --> 00:08:26.435
the bulge of southwest Africa
basically all around and have

00:08:26.435 --> 00:08:29.875
pushed other people's out and
the Pygmies are one of the

00:08:29.875 --> 00:08:33.375
groups that have been very
severely discriminated against

00:08:33.375 --> 00:08:36.440
and really pushed into
inhospitable places.

00:08:36.440 --> 00:08:41.293
Another example is the Bushmen
of Africa who were pushed into

00:08:41.293 --> 00:08:44.610
the Kalahari Desert in southern
Africa.

00:08:44.610 --> 00:08:49.250
Even in the desert these guys
eat 85 different species of

00:08:49.250 --> 00:08:52.121
plants,
and it's almost inconceivable

00:08:52.121 --> 00:08:54.798
in their culture,
for someone to die of

00:08:54.798 --> 00:08:59.023
starvation because plants will
bloom some years and not bloom

00:08:59.023 --> 00:09:00.149
some years.
 

00:09:00.149 --> 00:09:03.076
They will get a fungus some
year, or a virus,

00:09:03.076 --> 00:09:06.870
plants--any one species is not
generally very reliable.

00:09:06.870 --> 00:09:10.889
When you have 85 different
species to survive on you're not

00:09:10.889 --> 00:09:12.759
going to go without food.
 

00:09:12.759 --> 00:09:17.462
There will always be some group
of plants that are going to be

00:09:17.462 --> 00:09:21.548
available to you and so you're
not going to starve.

00:09:21.548 --> 00:09:24.924
Further, the anthropologists
lived with these people and they

00:09:24.924 --> 00:09:28.470
start writing down what they're
doing at every point in time.

00:09:28.470 --> 00:09:32.085
Per hour invested,
the Bushmen get more food then

00:09:32.085 --> 00:09:34.269
the early agriculturalists.
 

00:09:34.269 --> 00:09:39.633
Not modern agriculturalists who
can drive a tractor and in an

00:09:39.633 --> 00:09:42.582
hour do a lot,
but we're comparing

00:09:42.582 --> 00:09:47.590
hunter-gatherers to the first
stages of agriculture.

00:09:47.590 --> 00:09:52.350
The Kalahari--the Bushmen in
Kalahari spent 12 to 19 hours a

00:09:52.350 --> 00:09:57.191
week collecting food and the
rest of the time they used for a

00:09:57.191 --> 00:10:00.500
lot more sleep than current
farmers,

00:10:00.500 --> 00:10:04.000
and a lot more leisure than
farming people,

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:08.908
so life is more generous to
them.

00:10:08.908 --> 00:10:11.062
You have to think now,
this is for people pushed into

00:10:11.062 --> 00:10:13.244
a desert,
a very inhospitable place,

00:10:13.244 --> 00:10:16.828
and now if they--
if you can imagine them living

00:10:16.828 --> 00:10:20.700
in a lush forest region where
they originated,

00:10:20.700 --> 00:10:25.179
life must have been much,
much easier so the amount of

00:10:25.179 --> 00:10:30.506
time exerted to get your basics
of food and everything must have

00:10:30.506 --> 00:10:32.788
been much-- a lot less.
 

00:10:32.788 --> 00:10:38.172
Not only do they have to work
less and they get more food per

00:10:38.172 --> 00:10:40.879
hour,
but the variety of foods is

00:10:40.879 --> 00:10:45.009
very good for you because you
need different minerals,

00:10:45.009 --> 00:10:46.690
you need different other
micronutrients,

00:10:46.690 --> 00:10:51.519
you need different vitamins,
and as we are bombarded with in

00:10:51.519 --> 00:10:55.982
the popular press,
a variety of foods is very good

00:10:55.982 --> 00:10:56.779
for you.
 

00:10:56.779 --> 00:11:00.450
You don't want to eat just one
kind of food,

00:11:00.450 --> 00:11:05.058
so they had a very diverse and
healthy kind of diet.

00:11:05.058 --> 00:11:09.716
Agriculture comes in and indeed
it enormously increases the

00:11:09.716 --> 00:11:13.570
amount of food per acre when
land is limited,

00:11:13.570 --> 00:11:16.265
when you have a population
density such that land becomes

00:11:16.265 --> 00:11:18.528
limiting rather than your time
or your need,

00:11:18.528 --> 00:11:22.461
when land becomes limiting then
agriculture becomes important

00:11:22.461 --> 00:11:26.066
because per acre you can get a
lot more food than hunter

00:11:26.066 --> 00:11:29.398
gathering,
but you have to spend lots and

00:11:29.398 --> 00:11:34.408
lots of hours to get that land
to give you that amount of food.

00:11:34.408 --> 00:11:39.846
The question remains 'why are
there are--why were there and

00:11:39.846 --> 00:11:44.626
still are of course,
why are there are so few hunter

00:11:44.626 --> 00:11:45.940
gatherers?
 

00:11:45.940 --> 00:11:49.428
Again, a Malthusian type
question that,

00:11:49.428 --> 00:11:52.351
if we know they lived quite
well, we know that later people

00:11:52.351 --> 00:11:55.475
going into agriculture lived a
lot less well in terms of basics

00:11:55.475 --> 00:11:58.366
of life,
how come the hunter gatherer

00:11:58.366 --> 00:12:03.160
population did not increase up
to the same level of misery as

00:12:03.160 --> 00:12:06.745
early farmers,
which is basically one of the

00:12:06.745 --> 00:12:10.370
earliest examples of a
Malthusian type question.

00:12:10.370 --> 00:12:15.070
Malthus thought those same kind
of thoughts but for a much later

00:12:15.070 --> 00:12:16.038
population.
 

00:12:16.038 --> 00:12:20.102
Well in truth,
we don't really know the answer

00:12:20.102 --> 00:12:25.611
to this and it's greatly argued
about, but I can tell you some

00:12:25.611 --> 00:12:27.960
things that are known.
 

00:12:27.960 --> 00:12:31.856
Current hunter gatherers have a
moderate number of children and

00:12:31.856 --> 00:12:32.798
many survive.
 

00:12:32.798 --> 00:12:35.586
They do not have an enormous
infant mortality,

00:12:35.586 --> 00:12:39.426
certainly not compared to later
populations which I'll show you

00:12:39.426 --> 00:12:41.779
that have a huge infant
mortality.

00:12:41.779 --> 00:12:44.402
If they are Nomadic,
and I'll tell you about an

00:12:44.402 --> 00:12:47.311
example of that later,
they have to move quite a lot

00:12:47.311 --> 00:12:49.820
and that means carrying children
around.

00:12:49.820 --> 00:12:52.000
I think Bonnie has sort of
indicated to you,

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:54.428
even dealing with a lot of
children in one place is

00:12:54.428 --> 00:12:57.605
difficult,
but the difficulty of moving

00:12:57.605 --> 00:13:01.110
with very young children,
and packing up everything and

00:13:01.110 --> 00:13:03.989
moving for a very long time,
over a long distance is

00:13:03.989 --> 00:13:08.735
difficult and Nomadic peoples
very often show very clear signs

00:13:08.735 --> 00:13:12.470
of some form of conscious
population control.

00:13:12.470 --> 00:13:15.799
They know they can't cope with
more than "x"

00:13:15.799 --> 00:13:17.120
number of children.
 

00:13:17.120 --> 00:13:20.697
We'll get to that all societies
have indeed controlled their

00:13:20.697 --> 00:13:23.730
population but mechanism they
were not totally--

00:13:23.730 --> 00:13:27.245
not clear what they think the
reason for their doing things

00:13:27.245 --> 00:13:29.374
were,
but Nomads apparently know what

00:13:29.374 --> 00:13:30.168
they're doing.
 

00:13:30.168 --> 00:13:33.269
Hunter gatherers are moderately
healthy.

00:13:33.269 --> 00:13:36.701
Again, their burden of sickness
is not severe,

00:13:36.701 --> 00:13:39.600
again compared to later
populations;

00:13:39.600 --> 00:13:44.120
however parasites are always a
problem.

00:13:44.120 --> 00:13:47.070
I'll show you again a modern
case of parasites.

00:13:47.070 --> 00:13:48.613
This is a girl,
modern girl,

00:13:48.613 --> 00:13:51.700
current girl in Central
America, and you may notice the

00:13:51.700 --> 00:13:52.730
swollen belly.
 

00:13:52.730 --> 00:13:58.918
You know what's inside there to
swell it?

00:13:58.918 --> 00:14:04.758
Worms--exactly and when they
purge her that was what was

00:14:04.758 --> 00:14:08.580
inside that girl,
all those worms.

00:14:08.580 --> 00:14:13.080
Humans have had this problem
since time in memorial.

00:14:13.080 --> 00:14:16.639
Hunter gatherers are not immune
to this.

00:14:16.639 --> 00:14:20.580
Infectious diseases they have
less because they're in small

00:14:20.580 --> 00:14:23.023
groups,
so infectious diseases as you

00:14:23.023 --> 00:14:26.793
know need large groups to keep
spreading and they're hostile to

00:14:26.793 --> 00:14:29.212
their neighbors,
just again like chimpanzees so

00:14:29.212 --> 00:14:31.340
they don't come in a lot of
contact with neighbors,

00:14:31.340 --> 00:14:35.014
so diseases don't spread from
group to group and each

00:14:35.014 --> 00:14:38.690
individual group is not large
enough to allow for the

00:14:38.690 --> 00:14:40.740
maintenance of a disease.
 

00:14:40.740 --> 00:14:44.986
Each village,
if you--anthropologists go and

00:14:44.986 --> 00:14:50.322
sit in one village for a long
time and they have a high

00:14:50.322 --> 00:14:52.990
population growth rate.
 

00:14:52.990 --> 00:14:56.279
Each village seems to be
expanding quite noticeably,

00:14:56.279 --> 00:14:58.847
and you think,
well in each village that we go

00:14:58.847 --> 00:15:02.744
study population is increasing,
again, it doesn't make sense

00:15:02.744 --> 00:15:06.316
why haven't they--
been living that way a hundred

00:15:06.316 --> 00:15:08.842
thousand years,
why haven't they filled up

00:15:08.842 --> 00:15:09.470
their space?
 

00:15:09.470 --> 00:15:14.066
Why is each village surrounded
by lots of--basically unused

00:15:14.066 --> 00:15:14.700
space?
 

00:15:14.700 --> 00:15:18.322
Even today, a lot of the very
tropical lands are not

00:15:18.322 --> 00:15:20.168
high--densely populated.
 

00:15:20.168 --> 00:15:23.210
We may have the image that they
are but they're not.

00:15:23.210 --> 00:15:25.230
New Guinea is not densely
populated.

00:15:25.230 --> 00:15:27.836
If you call densely
populated--the Netherlands is I

00:15:27.836 --> 00:15:30.389
think the most densely populated
in the world,

00:15:30.389 --> 00:15:33.048
Bangladesh, the livable regions
of China,

00:15:33.048 --> 00:15:36.879
the livable regions of Japan,
these are densely populated.

00:15:36.879 --> 00:15:43.769
The tropical regions of the
world, nothing like that;

00:15:43.769 --> 00:15:46.970
New Guinea I said,
Borneo very sparsely populated,

00:15:46.970 --> 00:15:51.700
the Amazon, Sub-Saharan Africa
vast open areas,

00:15:51.700 --> 00:15:55.779
so these are not situations of
high population density,

00:15:55.779 --> 00:16:01.460
yet any village that you sit in
is increasing its population.

00:16:01.460 --> 00:16:04.720
What's going on?
 

00:16:04.720 --> 00:16:08.196
What are the--what the
archeologists find out is that

00:16:08.196 --> 00:16:11.605
when they study a site,
and I sort of mentioned this

00:16:11.605 --> 00:16:13.879
already, what you see is this.
 

00:16:13.879 --> 00:16:19.125
You go to--you start digging a
site and you actually dig in

00:16:19.125 --> 00:16:21.912
reserve,
but you go to the bottom and

00:16:21.912 --> 00:16:25.370
you see there was nobody there
before certain years,

00:16:25.370 --> 00:16:27.720
and then a small population,
and what you see,

00:16:27.720 --> 00:16:30.220
you can count the amount of
food remains,

00:16:30.220 --> 00:16:33.364
all kinds of things,
the population grows more or

00:16:33.364 --> 00:16:34.740
less exponentially.
 

00:16:34.740 --> 00:16:37.019
That means that the same
percentage every year.

00:16:37.019 --> 00:16:39.639
A half of a percent a year or
whatever it is,

00:16:39.639 --> 00:16:43.171
and it grows up faster and
faster, because there are more

00:16:43.171 --> 00:16:46.830
people producing that same
percent of population growth.

00:16:46.830 --> 00:16:50.095
You get this phase and then all
of a sudden you reach the top of

00:16:50.095 --> 00:16:53.360
your pile and your village is
gone and there's nothing there.

00:16:53.360 --> 00:16:57.803
Some sort of a crash happened,
where if it's not totally gone

00:16:57.803 --> 00:17:00.840
it's really knocked down
tremendously,

00:17:00.840 --> 00:17:04.634
and then you either wait--look
at that site again like the

00:17:04.634 --> 00:17:08.561
biblical sites which they dig,
and dig, and dig and sometime

00:17:08.561 --> 00:17:12.384
later starts up again,
or a different site starts up

00:17:12.384 --> 00:17:15.108
again and you get the same
phenomenon.

00:17:15.108 --> 00:17:17.528
Forget this line,
this is the idea of -- the

00:17:17.528 --> 00:17:20.116
carrying capacity,
but you can see nothing fits

00:17:20.116 --> 00:17:21.578
the carrying capacity.
 

00:17:21.578 --> 00:17:25.199
It just maybe stays there for a
little here, so the idea of

00:17:25.199 --> 00:17:28.568
carrying capacity for humans
doesn't work very well.

00:17:28.568 --> 00:17:33.038
What are the reasons--so--then
the explanation for the

00:17:33.038 --> 00:17:38.265
population staying more or less
constant and not filling up the

00:17:38.265 --> 00:17:42.650
space is not that each community
doesn't exist,

00:17:42.650 --> 00:17:45.964
but communities--here's your
space filled with community A,

00:17:45.964 --> 00:17:48.936
B, C, D, E and as each
community increases some other

00:17:48.936 --> 00:17:51.490
community just disappears,
goes out of existence.

00:17:51.490 --> 00:17:55.226
If you measure over the whole
big space you have a floating

00:17:55.226 --> 00:17:58.190
game of different communities
each growing,

00:17:58.190 --> 00:18:01.299
but then disappearing
completely, and the population

00:18:01.299 --> 00:18:04.348
and the whole space stays more
or less the same.

00:18:04.348 --> 00:18:07.255
I don't want to push that as it
really becomes super duper

00:18:07.255 --> 00:18:10.108
constant, but more or less the
same--does not fill up.

00:18:10.108 --> 00:18:13.648
What are the reasons why a
community would grow very

00:18:13.648 --> 00:18:16.077
happily, more or less,
very vaguely,

00:18:16.077 --> 00:18:19.410
exponentially,
and then go out of existence?

00:18:19.410 --> 00:18:21.759
One is of course climatic
disaster.

00:18:21.759 --> 00:18:26.704
There could be a freeze;
there could be a drought,

00:18:26.704 --> 00:18:31.645
these real climatic things,
and if you look at the Anasazi

00:18:31.645 --> 00:18:37.368
of Arizona that lived near the
Colorado River regions,

00:18:37.368 --> 00:18:39.782
one of the thoughts--they're
one of the communities that fit

00:18:39.782 --> 00:18:40.068
this.
 

00:18:40.068 --> 00:18:41.987
They're healthy,
you go see their ruins,

00:18:41.987 --> 00:18:43.608
and then they just disappeared.
 

00:18:43.608 --> 00:18:47.038
How many of you have been to
Anazasi site in Arizona?

00:18:47.038 --> 00:18:51.900
Just one student,
something you've got to do.

00:18:51.900 --> 00:18:55.386
There you're living in a
semi--a true desert now and a

00:18:55.386 --> 00:18:58.413
semi-desert back then,
so climatic things are a

00:18:58.413 --> 00:19:00.190
reasonable explanation.
 

00:19:00.190 --> 00:19:04.015
You go into the tropical
regions you don't have droughts

00:19:04.015 --> 00:19:07.771
that last, you don't have
freezes, and yet you see this

00:19:07.771 --> 00:19:09.720
same kind of phenomenon.
 

00:19:09.720 --> 00:19:14.557
While undoubtedly climatic
things happened occasionally in

00:19:14.557 --> 00:19:18.193
the temperate zones,
certainly in the northern

00:19:18.193 --> 00:19:21.969
zones, most hunter gatherer
societies probably that's not

00:19:21.969 --> 00:19:23.250
the explanation.
 

00:19:23.250 --> 00:19:27.151
The next thing is diseases of
the crops, that some fungus came

00:19:27.151 --> 00:19:29.068
by and wiped out your crops.
 

00:19:29.068 --> 00:19:32.756
Well we've just talked about
that, that since they're eating

00:19:32.756 --> 00:19:35.630
85 different kinds of things in
the desert,

00:19:35.630 --> 00:19:39.625
there isn't any kind of
microorganism that cuts across

00:19:39.625 --> 00:19:44.705
species like that,
so that explanation doesn't

00:19:44.705 --> 00:19:46.519
seem to work.
 

00:19:46.519 --> 00:19:49.196
Diseases of humans,
same thing, not diseases of

00:19:49.196 --> 00:19:51.499
plants,
but diseases of humans,

00:19:51.499 --> 00:19:54.490
again, the data just doesn't
fit that,

00:19:54.490 --> 00:19:59.115
that because of the isolation
they don't have a huge problem

00:19:59.115 --> 00:20:01.390
with communicable diseases.
 

00:20:01.390 --> 00:20:05.943
That leaves the possibility of
violent confrontation from one

00:20:05.943 --> 00:20:07.690
community to another.
 

00:20:07.690 --> 00:20:11.234
We've seen in the chimps how
the northern group will

00:20:11.234 --> 00:20:14.990
completely wipe out the southern
group and so forth.

00:20:14.990 --> 00:20:19.124
What kind of evidence can one
adduce that this might be what's

00:20:19.124 --> 00:20:19.868
going on?
 

00:20:19.868 --> 00:20:25.726
If one looks at any modern
population and looks at the

00:20:25.726 --> 00:20:30.807
survival curve,
so this is the number of deaths

00:20:30.807 --> 00:20:33.348
per 1,000 per year.
 

00:20:33.348 --> 00:20:35.487
This is India,
for instance,

00:20:35.487 --> 00:20:38.019
and it's fairly recent--1960s.
 

00:20:38.019 --> 00:20:41.440
Antibiotics are just coming in
at this stage,

00:20:41.440 --> 00:20:44.558
so very high infant mortality
rate,

00:20:44.558 --> 00:20:48.952
80 per 1,000--one out of every
12 kids dies almost immediately

00:20:48.952 --> 00:20:52.480
and then that high rate
continues until about--

00:20:52.480 --> 00:20:56.635
comes down to something about
six or seven years old so a lot

00:20:56.635 --> 00:21:00.170
of your population is just wiped
out immediately.

00:21:00.170 --> 00:21:05.016
Then you have a pretty low
level of death and fairly flat

00:21:05.016 --> 00:21:09.949
until it gets to be what's
considered old age in different

00:21:09.949 --> 00:21:13.930
populations and then the death
rate rises.

00:21:13.930 --> 00:21:16.328
You have this very standard
u-shaped curve,

00:21:16.328 --> 00:21:19.028
and here after you have sort of
modern medicine--

00:21:19.028 --> 00:21:21.240
this is Sweden in the same year
as the infant--

00:21:21.240 --> 00:21:24.413
primarily the main thing is the
infant mortality drops like

00:21:24.413 --> 00:21:28.318
crazy and the old age stuff--
everything drops but the main

00:21:28.318 --> 00:21:30.528
drop is in infant mortality.
 

00:21:30.528 --> 00:21:32.788
The idea is--what I just want
you to get out of this--

00:21:32.788 --> 00:21:36.660
we'll see this graph again and
again in a couple of times,

00:21:36.660 --> 00:21:40.449
is that during the adult years
the death rate is very low

00:21:40.449 --> 00:21:42.750
compared to either here or here.
 

00:21:42.750 --> 00:21:48.901
Now if you look at what we can
gather from archeological data

00:21:48.901 --> 00:21:53.821
from hunter gatherer
communities, you have a high

00:21:53.821 --> 00:21:56.180
death rate of kids.
 

00:21:56.180 --> 00:21:58.371
Not as high as when you get all
these communicable diseases in

00:21:58.371 --> 00:22:00.414
modern societies,
and then you have a flat

00:22:00.414 --> 00:22:03.509
period, and then all of a sudden
there's this big bump.

00:22:03.509 --> 00:22:07.470
What they call an excess
mortality in exactly the young

00:22:07.470 --> 00:22:10.007
adult years,
and then it comes back down

00:22:10.007 --> 00:22:13.150
again and you get a more or less
normal old age situation.

00:22:13.150 --> 00:22:16.849
Well what is it that kills
people in their middle years?

00:22:16.849 --> 00:22:19.240
Violence.
 

00:22:19.240 --> 00:22:22.470
So this kind of data--again we
don't totally--

00:22:22.470 --> 00:22:25.384
we don't really know the
answer, but this kind of data

00:22:25.384 --> 00:22:28.740
leads you to suspect that indeed
one of the major reasons,

00:22:28.740 --> 00:22:32.527
not the only reason,
but a major reason that the

00:22:32.527 --> 00:22:36.877
hunter gatherer communities and
the early archeological

00:22:36.877 --> 00:22:41.308
communities disappear so
suddenly is that they are wiped

00:22:41.308 --> 00:22:44.130
out by some sort of violence.
 

00:22:44.130 --> 00:22:49.904
We're right back in hunter
gatherer times as far as we can

00:22:49.904 --> 00:22:54.868
tell to what you've seen before
of these mass--

00:22:54.868 --> 00:22:59.895
I've showed you last time these
mass graves that are

00:22:59.895 --> 00:23:03.048
characteristic of this period.
 

00:23:03.048 --> 00:23:06.711
Okay, nevertheless,
over the very long scale of

00:23:06.711 --> 00:23:09.057
time--
our period of being cavemen and

00:23:09.057 --> 00:23:12.200
hunter gatherers lasted hundreds
of thousands of years--

00:23:12.200 --> 00:23:16.068
but gradually population did
slowly increase,

00:23:16.068 --> 00:23:20.367
and as population increases,
the land available to people

00:23:20.367 --> 00:23:21.288
gets less.
 

00:23:21.288 --> 00:23:23.920
We talk, I think next time
about Africa,

00:23:23.920 --> 00:23:27.383
which has a culture where land
is not a scarce commodity and

00:23:27.383 --> 00:23:30.722
now it's getting to be scarce,
but in their traditions,

00:23:30.722 --> 00:23:32.769
land is not the scarce
commodity,

00:23:32.769 --> 00:23:37.645
but as the population grows the
land per person gets less and

00:23:37.645 --> 00:23:42.441
then you have to make a more
intense utilization of the land

00:23:42.441 --> 00:23:44.880
and farming gets invented.
 

00:23:44.880 --> 00:23:48.069
A big discussion whether it
actually was the population

00:23:48.069 --> 00:23:51.732
pressure that caused farming to
be invented or whether that was

00:23:51.732 --> 00:23:55.160
just some brilliant stroke by
somebody that invented--

00:23:55.160 --> 00:23:58.519
that people slowly figured it
out.

00:23:58.519 --> 00:24:04.150
They actually can trace the
origin of agriculture to--

00:24:04.150 --> 00:24:07.519
the current data is 11,700
years ago in the Middle East,

00:24:07.519 --> 00:24:10.772
in Anatolia,
what's now Turkey,

00:24:10.772 --> 00:24:14.909
now eastern Turkey,
and it expands on the average

00:24:14.909 --> 00:24:18.589
from the original sites you can
watch it expand and it expands

00:24:18.589 --> 00:24:20.220
at one kilometer a year.
 

00:24:20.220 --> 00:24:21.390
That's the average.
 

00:24:21.390 --> 00:24:25.269
Then it eventually takes over
the whole world.

00:24:25.269 --> 00:24:27.570
The number of people,
and when you invent

00:24:27.570 --> 00:24:30.851
agriculture, the number of
people that can be supported on

00:24:30.851 --> 00:24:33.210
one plot of land grows up
enormously.

00:24:33.210 --> 00:24:36.556
We've seen that and so these
people become more numerous and

00:24:36.556 --> 00:24:39.960
so in military confrontations
and warlike confrontations,

00:24:39.960 --> 00:24:42.150
they're going to be dominant,
almost no matter what the

00:24:42.150 --> 00:24:44.921
technology is,
no matter what the bravery is,

00:24:44.921 --> 00:24:49.083
if you have an awful lot more
people you're going to wipe out

00:24:49.083 --> 00:24:53.038
or push out groups that don't
have that kind of population

00:24:53.038 --> 00:24:53.940
density.
 

00:24:53.940 --> 00:24:57.442
Agriculture spreads;
in the early days of

00:24:57.442 --> 00:25:02.612
agriculture you don't know an
awful lot yet and you probably

00:25:02.612 --> 00:25:07.078
have one crop that you really
know how to grow.

00:25:07.078 --> 00:25:08.864
For instance,
in the Americas,

00:25:08.864 --> 00:25:12.555
the big crop was corn that most
of Latin America even to this

00:25:12.555 --> 00:25:16.317
day lives on corn,
and the North American Indians

00:25:16.317 --> 00:25:17.960
lived a lot on corn.
 

00:25:17.960 --> 00:25:20.740
Of course in Southeast Asia a
great big population,

00:25:20.740 --> 00:25:22.939
it was rice,
and you basically lived off

00:25:22.939 --> 00:25:27.215
most of your calories,
most of your food from one

00:25:27.215 --> 00:25:28.650
single crop.
 

00:25:28.650 --> 00:25:33.328
That's not very healthy because
each crop is missing something.

00:25:33.328 --> 00:25:36.248
Corn, you may know,
misses lysine,

00:25:36.248 --> 00:25:41.465
one of these essential amino
acids and over a very long time

00:25:41.465 --> 00:25:46.519
the Americans learned to--
a rather complicated procedure

00:25:46.519 --> 00:25:51.078
for boiling it in lime to
extract this amino acid from the

00:25:51.078 --> 00:25:53.644
plant,
but until that was discovered

00:25:53.644 --> 00:25:56.140
they must have been extremely
unhealthy.

00:25:56.140 --> 00:25:58.970
Rice, you know,
is missing all kinds of

00:25:58.970 --> 00:26:03.365
vitamins and people have very
severe vitamin deficiencies if

00:26:03.365 --> 00:26:05.750
their diet is too much rice.
 

00:26:05.750 --> 00:26:10.362
You're not getting a health--in
early farming you're not getting

00:26:10.362 --> 00:26:14.901
a particularly healthy diet and
you're not getting the vitamins

00:26:14.901 --> 00:26:17.608
and micronutrients that you
need.

00:26:17.608 --> 00:26:19.838
Furthermore,
your food security goes down.

00:26:19.838 --> 00:26:23.078
Again, as I've mentioned,
that a virus or a fungus,

00:26:23.078 --> 00:26:26.388
or something attacks your
crops, and that's 80% of your

00:26:26.388 --> 00:26:29.759
calories and that is wiped out
in a year you're gone.

00:26:29.759 --> 00:26:34.750
Or if locusts come by and eat
them up or some insect

00:26:34.750 --> 00:26:37.490
infestation comes through.
 

00:26:37.490 --> 00:26:44.848
Also an increase in calorie
availability;

00:26:44.848 --> 00:26:49.695
you can--more people can stay
alive and so you get dense

00:26:49.695 --> 00:26:50.930
populations.
 

00:26:50.930 --> 00:26:54.807
The social structure changes,
now previously each person

00:26:54.807 --> 00:26:58.827
could only get enough food
basically for himself and maybe

00:26:58.827 --> 00:27:00.519
a very small family.
 

00:27:00.519 --> 00:27:03.221
As you develop the technology
of agriculture,

00:27:03.221 --> 00:27:06.474
an individual can produce a
surplus, not everything he

00:27:06.474 --> 00:27:07.088
feeds.
 

00:27:07.088 --> 00:27:09.338
Well who's going to get that
surplus?

00:27:09.338 --> 00:27:13.573
In an egalitarian society he
keeps the surplus himself,

00:27:13.573 --> 00:27:15.690
his family, and so forth.
 

00:27:15.690 --> 00:27:19.284
But there's other guys that are
either stronger and nastier then

00:27:19.284 --> 00:27:22.480
you and they come in and steal
your surplus from you,

00:27:22.480 --> 00:27:24.813
and they have to leave you just
with a small part of your

00:27:24.813 --> 00:27:27.188
production to just keep you
alive because they want you to

00:27:27.188 --> 00:27:30.410
work for them,
and so you get societies now

00:27:30.410 --> 00:27:32.578
where there are classes.
 

00:27:32.578 --> 00:27:36.077
There are people who in way or
another take the excess food

00:27:36.077 --> 00:27:38.789
from the farmer and use it for
other purposes,

00:27:38.789 --> 00:27:40.660
usually their own purposes.
 

00:27:40.660 --> 00:27:44.750
They can largely hire military
to keep them in power and to

00:27:44.750 --> 00:27:47.078
protect them from other places.
 

00:27:47.078 --> 00:27:51.123
That's a large use of the food
surplus which agriculture puts

00:27:51.123 --> 00:27:51.460
up.
 

00:27:51.460 --> 00:27:55.608
Also manufacturers come in;
they hire artisans to make

00:27:55.608 --> 00:27:59.338
beautiful gold objects for them,
or to make beds,

00:27:59.338 --> 00:28:03.038
or chairs or all the
manufacturing starts on the

00:28:03.038 --> 00:28:07.522
agricultural surplus that
agriculture brings in because an

00:28:07.522 --> 00:28:12.403
individual human now can produce
more calories than he needs to

00:28:12.403 --> 00:28:15.630
keep going at a subsistence
level.

00:28:15.630 --> 00:28:18.718
What you see as agriculture
progresses is the hunter

00:28:18.718 --> 00:28:22.108
gatherer societies are generally
quite an egalitarian.

00:28:22.108 --> 00:28:24.876
They'll more or less have a
head man but he won't--or a wise

00:28:24.876 --> 00:28:27.269
man or an old man,
but they won't have authority.

00:28:27.269 --> 00:28:29.298
He can't order other people
around;

00:28:29.298 --> 00:28:33.123
the community has to agree on
some project if they undertake

00:28:33.123 --> 00:28:34.288
projects at all.
 

00:28:34.288 --> 00:28:38.660
As more food wealth becomes
available,

00:28:38.660 --> 00:28:44.480
societies start stratifying,
you get social classes,

00:28:44.480 --> 00:28:49.446
you get castes,
and this inequality changes

00:28:49.446 --> 00:28:54.058
everything about the way humans
live.

00:28:54.058 --> 00:28:57.265
The congestion in the
cities--cities start growing up

00:28:57.265 --> 00:29:00.717
and then you start getting the
spread of these infectious

00:29:00.717 --> 00:29:04.169
diseases where one person
spreads it to the next in large

00:29:04.169 --> 00:29:06.078
agglomerations of humans.
 

00:29:06.078 --> 00:29:10.273
That just gets worse and worse
up through the 1400s in Europe

00:29:10.273 --> 00:29:14.400
when you get the Black Death and
wipes out a huge number.

00:29:14.400 --> 00:29:19.287
That is--as civilization
progresses the death rate from

00:29:19.287 --> 00:29:23.358
infectious diseases just keeps
going on up.

00:29:23.358 --> 00:29:27.512
Adding all this together and
the data we have,

00:29:27.512 --> 00:29:33.420
is that hunter gatherers--their
lifespan is ballpark 50 years.

00:29:33.420 --> 00:29:38.328
In early agriculture societies
that goes down to 35 years,

00:29:38.328 --> 00:29:43.965
so we're really--and I'll show
you data that in a lot of places

00:29:43.965 --> 00:29:47.328
it's probably even lower than
that.

00:29:47.328 --> 00:29:51.240
We have this situation where
humans--

00:29:51.240 --> 00:29:53.808
not counting violence that
humans live--

00:29:53.808 --> 00:29:55.710
when they weren't being
attacked by their neighbors,

00:29:55.710 --> 00:29:59.049
humans were living very well,
the hunter gatherer society;

00:29:59.049 --> 00:30:00.868
sort of Garden of Eden.
 

00:30:00.868 --> 00:30:04.140
Then agriculture comes in and
the vast mass of humans become

00:30:04.140 --> 00:30:06.505
peasants;
the land becomes owned not by

00:30:06.505 --> 00:30:09.749
them but by someone else,
and they have to give most of

00:30:09.749 --> 00:30:11.970
what they've produced to someone
else,

00:30:11.970 --> 00:30:13.858
so life becomes miserable.
 

00:30:13.858 --> 00:30:17.798
There's a lot of thought that
the various of Garden of Eden

00:30:17.798 --> 00:30:20.413
myths--
I mean almost every culture has

00:30:20.413 --> 00:30:24.359
some sort of glorification of a
very distant past where people

00:30:24.359 --> 00:30:26.430
did not have to work so hard.
 

00:30:26.430 --> 00:30:28.798
In our culture we call it the
Garden of Eden;

00:30:28.798 --> 00:30:31.688
everything was perfect,
then something happened,

00:30:31.688 --> 00:30:35.375
and after the fall of one sort
or another, now it's the sweat

00:30:35.375 --> 00:30:36.358
of our brow.
 

00:30:36.358 --> 00:30:39.895
It's a very nice description of
what I've been telling you of

00:30:39.895 --> 00:30:43.019
the hunter gatherers living in a
lush environment--

00:30:43.019 --> 00:30:44.740
before they're pushed into the
desert--

00:30:44.740 --> 00:30:47.434
living quite well,
and however,

00:30:47.434 --> 00:30:51.119
later on then they have to be
farmers,

00:30:51.119 --> 00:30:52.548
the sweat of the brow.
 

00:30:52.548 --> 00:30:59.980
And violence like Cain and Abel
is what is the fly in the

00:30:59.980 --> 00:31:05.288
ointment of that beautiful Eden
story.

00:31:05.288 --> 00:31:11.165
Now we come to the agricultural
period in our historical romp

00:31:11.165 --> 00:31:12.930
through history.
 

00:31:12.930 --> 00:31:17.013
There are some really
fundamental issues that you have

00:31:17.013 --> 00:31:21.945
to understand to understand what
was happening with population in

00:31:21.945 --> 00:31:23.180
these times.
 

00:31:23.180 --> 00:31:27.661
There's constraints on human
population, and the first was

00:31:27.661 --> 00:31:31.750
this enormous infant mortality
which I showed you.

00:31:31.750 --> 00:31:36.890
Again, we're looking at 1960
here in a very civilized place,

00:31:36.890 --> 00:31:41.733
poor India in 1960,
but still even into the 1960s

00:31:41.733 --> 00:31:47.079
where we're very modern,
the infant mortality is

00:31:47.079 --> 00:31:48.220
enormous.
 

00:31:48.220 --> 00:31:50.940
You go, even currently,
to a less well developed place,

00:31:50.940 --> 00:31:55.960
just cut out this quote from
Haiti in 1979,

00:31:55.960 --> 00:31:59.670
before this recent rash of
problems,

00:31:59.670 --> 00:32:02.660
a Cornell trained Haitian,
comes from Haiti to Cornell,

00:32:02.660 --> 00:32:05.568
gets a medical degree,
returns to Haiti,

00:32:05.568 --> 00:32:08.810
and he gets a job at a
pediatric hospital:

00:32:08.810 --> 00:32:12.367
"40% of the infants,
of the babies,"

00:32:12.367 --> 00:32:15.357
the birth rate--
he's working in among other

00:32:15.357 --> 00:32:18.626
things a maternity clinic,
"40% of the babies were

00:32:18.626 --> 00:32:20.368
dying of endemic diarrhea.
 

00:32:20.368 --> 00:32:25.304
A man would come to pick up the
