00:32:29.490 --> 00:32:35.368
And this is 1979 in--how far is
Haiti from Miami?

00:32:35.368 --> 00:32:39.470
A hundred and fifty miles or
something like that.

00:32:39.470 --> 00:32:45.112
The data--we have various data
sets for what life expectancy

00:32:45.112 --> 00:32:49.688
was like,
and this is various populations

00:32:49.688 --> 00:32:53.578
and what this is,
this is a survivorship curve.

00:32:53.578 --> 00:32:59.298
So you take--for 1,000 people
born in any given space of time,

00:32:59.298 --> 00:33:01.920
in an earlier period--so this
is Cisalpine Gaul,

00:33:01.920 --> 00:33:05.575
this is Roman times,
that's the part of Gaul that's

00:33:05.575 --> 00:33:08.720
this side of the Alps according
to them,

00:33:08.720 --> 00:33:11.660
Cisalpine Gaul.
 

00:33:11.660 --> 00:33:16.635
Out of 1,000 children born,
and actually this shows females

00:33:16.635 --> 00:33:21.698
but it's more or less the same
for males, almost immediately

00:33:21.698 --> 00:33:23.500
half of them die.
 

00:33:23.500 --> 00:33:30.233
That's very characteristic of
human societies until modern

00:33:30.233 --> 00:33:35.550
sanitation comes in,
which is in Europe 1700s,

00:33:35.550 --> 00:33:38.858
and in Asia maybe 1900s.
 

00:33:38.858 --> 00:33:43.576
You have this tremendous death
rate of children and then it

00:33:43.576 --> 00:33:48.130
continues at a fairly high but
decreasing death rate,

00:33:48.130 --> 00:33:50.848
and then finally there's very
few people left.

00:33:50.848 --> 00:33:53.589
This is not the curve which
showed you the percentage of

00:33:53.589 --> 00:33:55.981
death in age thing,
but how many people are still

00:33:55.981 --> 00:33:56.680
surviving?
 

00:33:56.680 --> 00:34:01.724
At any point in--by age 15
here, this dotted line,

00:34:01.724 --> 00:34:07.286
only about 40% of people are
still alive, 60% have died

00:34:07.286 --> 00:34:09.139
before age 15.
 

00:34:09.139 --> 00:34:11.789
This again is women,
so a lot of these deaths in

00:34:11.789 --> 00:34:14.175
this middle period,
by the time--this is the

00:34:14.175 --> 00:34:18.945
reproductive years,
these dotted lines is 15 to 45

00:34:18.945 --> 00:34:21.717
or so,
I think 50 in this case,

00:34:21.717 --> 00:34:25.989
which is the years in which
women can reproduce and most of

00:34:25.989 --> 00:34:30.409
the death in females in this
period is childbirth itself.

00:34:30.409 --> 00:34:32.829
In a developing population,
in a pre-medical population,

00:34:32.829 --> 00:34:37.599
childbirth itself is one of the
most dangerous things in these

00:34:37.599 --> 00:34:41.820
years and the death rates are
very high from childbirth

00:34:41.820 --> 00:34:46.030
itself,
so a lot of that is female--is

00:34:46.030 --> 00:34:47.340
childbirth.
 

00:34:47.340 --> 00:34:52.380
If you looked a male population
it might even be more extreme

00:34:52.380 --> 00:34:57.168
due to the--probably due to the
violence that we've talked

00:34:57.168 --> 00:34:58.010
about.
 

00:34:58.010 --> 00:35:00.257
Now as times goes on--we're
going to come back to this

00:35:00.257 --> 00:35:02.173
graph,
but as time goes on,

00:35:02.173 --> 00:35:05.780
this is Italy in 1921 and
things have gotten--

00:35:05.780 --> 00:35:09.068
at all ages the death is less,
so there's more people

00:35:09.068 --> 00:35:11.730
surviving,
and then you come to Japan;

00:35:11.730 --> 00:35:16.030
again 1984 and you have very,
very little infant mortality,

00:35:16.030 --> 00:35:20.278
very little mortality through
this period and then again old

00:35:20.278 --> 00:35:22.800
age takes over and people do
die.

00:35:22.800 --> 00:35:27.951
This kind of bump here compared
to say this, is again possibly

00:35:27.951 --> 00:35:31.920
violence in that era,
but again, we don't really

00:35:31.920 --> 00:35:32.679
know.
 

00:35:32.679 --> 00:35:34.869
For our purposes,
going back in time,

00:35:34.869 --> 00:35:38.181
we're really interested in this
lower graph which is

00:35:38.181 --> 00:35:41.880
characteristic of humans from
way back until really almost

00:35:41.880 --> 00:35:45.018
Napoleonic times,
maybe through Napoleonic times

00:35:45.018 --> 00:35:47.817
but the death--
the violence in Napoleonic

00:35:47.817 --> 00:35:49.268
times was enormous.
 

00:35:49.268 --> 00:35:52.208
If you look at women,
consider this just a graph for

00:35:52.208 --> 00:35:52.670
women.
 

00:35:52.670 --> 00:35:56.329
Of 1,000 women born,
400 are still alive at the

00:35:56.329 --> 00:36:01.181
beginning of their reproductive
period and about 200 are still

00:36:01.181 --> 00:36:05.159
alive at the end of their
reproductive period.

00:36:05.159 --> 00:36:08.311
If you average that out
something like--it would be the

00:36:08.311 --> 00:36:11.347
same as if something 300 women
lived throughout their

00:36:11.347 --> 00:36:12.750
reproductive period.
 

00:36:12.750 --> 00:36:17.280
Well, if that society is going
to keep going,

00:36:17.280 --> 00:36:23.148
what is needed to happen that
these more or less 300 women

00:36:23.148 --> 00:36:27.369
have to reproduce 1,000 women,
right?

00:36:27.369 --> 00:36:32.400
If they reproduce 1,000 women
they also have to reproduce

00:36:32.400 --> 00:36:33.570
1,000 boys.
 

00:36:33.570 --> 00:36:37.905
So 300 women have to give rise
to 2,000 children and if they

00:36:37.905 --> 00:36:42.021
don't do that then there's fewer
and fewer people in each

00:36:42.021 --> 00:36:46.800
generation and rapidly you don't
see this population anymore.

00:36:46.800 --> 00:36:50.239
How many children is that that
each woman has to have?

00:36:50.239 --> 00:36:53.730
Three hundred women making
2,000 children--

00:36:53.730 --> 00:36:57.570
6 2/3, almost 7,
so that means that in--

00:36:57.570 --> 00:37:00.260
when you have a mortality curve
like this,

00:37:00.260 --> 00:37:02.800
which again is most of human
recorded history,

00:37:02.800 --> 00:37:06.097
most of human history not
counting hunter gatherers who

00:37:06.097 --> 00:37:09.326
did live longer apparently,
the absolute minimum that a

00:37:09.326 --> 00:37:12.429
society could cope with is women
have basically an average of

00:37:12.429 --> 00:37:13.360
seven children.
 

00:37:13.360 --> 00:37:17.061
Wait a minute,
I've made this a better case,

00:37:17.061 --> 00:37:21.967
that's of the--all that this
graph shows is women that are

00:37:21.967 --> 00:37:24.119
alive in this period.
 

00:37:24.119 --> 00:37:26.320
What fraction go infertile?
 

00:37:26.320 --> 00:37:28.480
What fraction have infertile
husbands?

00:37:28.480 --> 00:37:30.170
What fraction never get married?
 

00:37:30.170 --> 00:37:32.679
What fraction are too sick to
have children?

00:37:32.679 --> 00:37:36.931
What fraction of women are worn
out after two or three children

00:37:36.931 --> 00:37:38.440
and can't bear many?
 

00:37:38.440 --> 00:37:41.760
That's also a very large number
which depends on the population,

00:37:41.760 --> 00:37:45.195
so if you subtract those--let's
call them infertile women for a

00:37:45.195 --> 00:37:48.190
variety of reasons in which they
or their husbands,

00:37:48.190 --> 00:37:53.539
or their health they're
infertile, then there's even

00:37:53.539 --> 00:37:58.260
fewer people alive and so this
curve goes--

00:37:58.260 --> 00:38:01.807
if you didn't graph just women
alive but women that are alive

00:38:01.807 --> 00:38:05.572
and in childbearing condition,
the curve gets much lower,

00:38:05.572 --> 00:38:08.289
so the number of children that
women--

00:38:08.289 --> 00:38:12.177
the women that were physically
capable of it had to have in

00:38:12.177 --> 00:38:15.260
these pre-modern times was more
than seven,

00:38:15.260 --> 00:38:19.085
and probably eight or nine,
or you have to do the

00:38:19.085 --> 00:38:23.630
calculation and people don't
know how to evaluate the--

00:38:23.630 --> 00:38:29.340
what fraction of Roman women
were fertile or infertile?

00:38:29.340 --> 00:38:31.969
You can't calculate that.
 

00:38:31.969 --> 00:38:40.518
We have a huge problem that
somehow there must be cul--

00:38:40.518 --> 00:38:43.909
there must be mechanisms to
insure that no women are wasted,

00:38:43.909 --> 00:38:46.730
that any woman that can
reproduce does reproduce,

00:38:46.730 --> 00:38:49.480
and when they reproduce they go
at it.

00:38:49.480 --> 00:38:53.405
They just keep going and going,
and of course men have an equal

00:38:53.405 --> 00:38:57.079
part--well they don't do the
amount of work but they have a

00:38:57.079 --> 00:38:58.030
part in it.
 

00:38:58.030 --> 00:39:03.123
As I said, this level of
mortality continues into quite

00:39:03.123 --> 00:39:06.518
modern times,
it's quite striking.

00:39:06.518 --> 00:39:11.001
Europe got out of it a little
bit earlier, I say somewhere in

00:39:11.001 --> 00:39:15.110
1700s, but for instance in 1912
in Australia--we have an

00:39:15.110 --> 00:39:16.530
Australian T.A.
 

00:39:16.530 --> 00:39:17.820
is she here today?
 

00:39:17.820 --> 00:39:22.688
Went to the--she got a ticket
to the inauguration--1912

00:39:22.688 --> 00:39:27.827
Australian census shows that 60%
of all children born died

00:39:27.827 --> 00:39:29.090
unmarried.
 

00:39:29.090 --> 00:39:32.083
That's this number,
we have them--well it was about

00:39:32.083 --> 00:39:35.737
the same number as this,
this shows that only 40% are

00:39:35.737 --> 00:39:39.159
left and this says in Australia
60% are dead,

00:39:39.159 --> 00:39:43.219
so that's the same number.
 

00:39:43.219 --> 00:39:46.090
Sixty percent of children born
died unmarried,

00:39:46.090 --> 00:39:49.480
and among the married one-ninth
of marriages were sterile,

00:39:49.480 --> 00:39:53.710
and just 11% of the men and 14%
of the women produced half of

00:39:53.710 --> 00:39:54.768
the children.
 

00:39:54.768 --> 00:39:59.632
That means those that could
reproduce and were married and

00:39:59.632 --> 00:40:03.472
had to really have very,
very high birthrates,

00:40:03.472 --> 00:40:05.179
as late as 1912.
 

00:40:05.179 --> 00:40:11.224
China, as late as 1930,
had a nearly aboriginal birth

00:40:11.224 --> 00:40:13.199
and death rate.
 

00:40:13.199 --> 00:40:17.094
The total fertility level was
at these levels of six,

00:40:17.094 --> 00:40:21.141
seven, eight children per
woman, yet the population was

00:40:21.141 --> 00:40:24.597
not increasing,
which means the death rate was

00:40:24.597 --> 00:40:28.315
just as high and they were in
this kind of a situation for

00:40:28.315 --> 00:40:29.360
reproduction.
 

00:40:29.360 --> 00:40:33.219
We're going to talk a lot about
China later of course.

00:40:33.219 --> 00:40:37.460
At that death rate,
and this is data for China,

00:40:37.460 --> 00:40:41.230
in order to have a 50%
certainty--so as you know many

00:40:41.230 --> 00:40:43.635
cultures,
and Chinese included in

00:40:43.635 --> 00:40:47.989
traditional times,
for sure wanted at least one

00:40:47.989 --> 00:40:49.929
child to survive.
 

00:40:49.929 --> 00:40:53.880
They do a calculation at this
death rate how many children is

00:40:53.880 --> 00:40:57.831
the minimum you have to have to
give yourself a 50% chance of

00:40:57.831 --> 00:41:01.159
having one son survive;
five children.

00:41:01.159 --> 00:41:04.969
If you're not thinking of
reproducing the population,

00:41:04.969 --> 00:41:08.172
but just reproducing your own
family which is the way

00:41:08.172 --> 00:41:12.360
individual families think,
and they have to have a son and

00:41:12.360 --> 00:41:16.650
you have this mortality rate,
at five children you have a 50%

00:41:16.650 --> 00:41:17.139
chance.
 

00:41:17.139 --> 00:41:19.838
If you want to have an 80%
chance of something you're back

00:41:19.838 --> 00:41:23.059
up to eight,
nine, ten children which

00:41:23.059 --> 00:41:26.394
explains the desire--
not necessarily--they don't

00:41:26.394 --> 00:41:28.889
necessarily keep this birth rate
but the desire for these very,

00:41:28.889 --> 00:41:31.679
very high birth rates.
 

00:41:31.679 --> 00:41:35.929
The result is that in most
pre-modern societies,

00:41:35.929 --> 00:41:40.358
women spend their whole
post-pubertal lives either

00:41:40.358 --> 00:41:42.710
pregnant or lactating.
 

00:41:42.710 --> 00:41:47.012
There's basically never a time
when they're free of the

00:41:47.012 --> 00:41:50.039
biological aspects of
childbearing,

00:41:50.039 --> 00:41:55.134
not counting the children that
are now not breastfeeding

00:41:55.134 --> 00:41:58.840
anymore that Bonnie was talking
about.

00:41:58.840 --> 00:42:01.583
For instance,
in Bangladesh in the 1990s,

00:42:01.583 --> 00:42:05.701
we're coming up very--75% of
the women in the age group of 20

00:42:05.701 --> 00:42:08.719
to 39 were either pregnant or
lactating.

00:42:08.719 --> 00:42:10.889
That means four out of every
five women were,

00:42:10.889 --> 00:42:12.690
at that moment,
any moment that you look,

00:42:12.690 --> 00:42:15.050
they're either pregnant or
breastfeeding,

00:42:15.050 --> 00:42:19.617
and there's a small period in
which they rest and then it

00:42:19.617 --> 00:42:21.250
starts over again.
 

00:42:21.250 --> 00:42:25.699
We're not talking--in the need
for these very high birth rates,

00:42:25.699 --> 00:42:29.059
we're not just talking about
primitive tribes by any means,

00:42:29.059 --> 00:42:33.182
we're talking about the period
in which all the world's great

00:42:33.182 --> 00:42:34.969
civilizations developed.
 

00:42:34.969 --> 00:42:38.715
Civilization--one of the things
that civilizations had to do was

00:42:38.715 --> 00:42:40.619
insure a birth rate like this.
 

00:42:40.619 --> 00:42:45.148
In the period in which cultures
were learning to write and

00:42:45.148 --> 00:42:49.878
producing a classic literature,
and developing the great world

00:42:49.878 --> 00:42:52.929
religions,
all of these if you read

00:42:52.929 --> 00:42:58.342
through them are calculated in
some sense to keep fertility

00:42:58.342 --> 00:42:59.090
high.
 

00:42:59.090 --> 00:43:03.230
All of these things glorify
high fertility.

00:43:03.230 --> 00:43:09.510
The religious doctrines push it;
there's community sanctions;

00:43:09.510 --> 00:43:12.860
the cultures just developed in
a way that--

00:43:12.860 --> 00:43:15.679
in order to increase fertility
and any culture that doesn't do

00:43:15.679 --> 00:43:17.760
that and doesn't increase it
successfully,

00:43:17.760 --> 00:43:19.239
they're just not here anymore.
 

00:43:19.239 --> 00:43:22.105
Of course most cultures that
you read about are not here

00:43:22.105 --> 00:43:24.190
anymore, and they were not
successful.

00:43:24.190 --> 00:43:28.927
In our Western culture,
the most famous of these things

00:43:28.927 --> 00:43:34.719
is the First Commandment in the
Bible: be fruitful and multiply.

00:43:34.719 --> 00:43:37.891
Well that fits us,
if you didn't do that then the

00:43:37.891 --> 00:43:41.128
Hebrews would be gone,
and we wouldn't have any of

00:43:41.128 --> 00:43:44.300
what we currently have in terms
of religion;

00:43:44.300 --> 00:43:46.340
any kind of the monotheistic
religions.

00:43:46.340 --> 00:43:50.780
There's all kinds--you look at
the culture--the religious

00:43:50.780 --> 00:43:55.061
tradition of any culture,
you'll find all kinds of laws

00:43:55.061 --> 00:43:57.518
about regulating sexuality.
 

